dismissalText.commentary: Shane Watson c Finn b Swann 66 (80b 8x4 0x6 133m) SR: 82.5

dismissalComment.html: lofted, high towards deep midwicket and Finn takes the catch low the ground ... Watson goes! Swann tempted Watson out of his crease, maybe dragged the length down a smidge, the batsman heaved high but it's a long boundary and Finn plunged forward to claim it

but this is edged behind! Goodness me I did not expect that, a little cutter outside off and Clarke feathers it low to Kieswetter. It was a good length and Clarke pushed at it and got a thing edge through to the keeper, good area from Bopara and a mistake from Clarke

dismissalText.commentary: David Warner c Bell b Finn 10 (20b 2x4 0x6 18m) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: and there is the wicket! Pulled straight up and into the hands of square leg. Big wicket for England and the extra pace of Finn tells again

dismissalComment.html: tossed up, tip and run to mid-off - and Brett Lee's direct hit sends Bopara back! That's a shame, he should have been there at the end, but a <del>matchwinning</del> [not yet, not yet] top knock from the Essex man

and he does strike! Bell goes to cut a ball that slid onto him and loses his off stump. It was too full for the stroke and a poor stroke first ball to a new bowler anyway, and Bell missed it and it ran onto off stump

dismissalComment.html: Trott advances on Watson, gets a faint inside edge, and the ball rattles the stumps! The ball was pretty similar to the one Bell hit out of the park but Trott played with an angled bat - where Bell's was straight - and Watson skidded it through the gap to disturb wicket. Trott's off and Aussies/aesthetes everywhere rejoice

commentTextItems.html: tossed up, bit of room and Morgan cuts, gets a bottom edge, it beats Wade, running away behind the stumps - that'll do it, they run the two needed, and England have won by six wickets with a good, solid handful of overs to spare

commentPostTextItems.html: 7.10pm: Victory at The Oval - England's first over Australia at this ground since 1997 - means Alastair Cook's side take a 2-0 lead in the five-match series. Australia's total looked a little soft and doughy, their batsmen having not quite done enough (despite George Bailey kicking on, his crawl to 26 off 60 balls epitomised their struggles) and England executed a textbook run chase on a good surface. A whiff of controversy will cling to Morgan's successful review - Hot Spot wasn't conclusive, so the decision shouldn't have been overturned, even though he seemed confident he'd hit the ball - but Bell and Bopara were excellent and England should have got there even without their lucky No. 5. Ravi Bopara was named Man of the Match and his run-a-ball knock was just the sort of composed-but-lively innings Australia couldn't muster. There's life in the series yet, however, and the tourists will need to regroup before Edgbaston on Wednesday. We'll be back to bring you full coverage - until then, keep working on rotating the strike. Cheerio

commentTextItems.html: round the wicket, turned on the front foot to midwicket

tossed up, tip and run to mid-off - and Brett Lee's direct hit sends Bopara back! That's a shame, he should have been there at the end, but a <del>matchwinning</del> [not yet, not yet] top knock from the Essex man

commentPostTextItems.html: Bopara has been putting pressure on the fielders to good effect all innings but finally ran out of luck. Is there going to be a dramatic final chapter here ...?

commentPreTextItems.html: Doughy to finish things (in all likelihood)

commentTextItems.html: length ball outside off, tapped to point
back of a length, on the stumps, turned to the man at short midwicket

commentPreTextItems.html: One blow will do it now ...

commentTextItems.html: length ball outside off, dabbed short of point
pitched up on the stumps, drives in the air over mid-off, into an unpatrolled area of the pitch
full, slightly wide, Morgan has a slash at it but misses
on leg stump, whipped behind square insouciantly by Morgan, who's ticking along like a beaut now
on the stumps, turned through the leg side
length delivery outside off, tickled through the cover region to the man in the deep

commentPostTextItems.html: So, England closing in on 2-0. [lights fuse, puts fingers in ears] The whitewash, which would make England No. 1 in all three formats, doesn't look quite such an outlandish suggestion now, does it?

commentTextItems.html: length ball outside off and Bopara swings a meaty pull shot through midwicket, it was briefly in the air but was travelling pretty quickly
good length ball outside off, pushed towards cover
defended back to the bowler and Lee nearly hits Bopara with a wild throw at the stumps, Wade does well to prevent overthrows

commentPostTextItems.html: "You say the DRS overturning of Eoin Morgan was an error of application and not failure of technology?" says Sukesh. "Wait a minute, isnt DRS there to fix errors of application in umpiring in first place. So what is next, DRS for DRS?" No - just umpires being taught to use it better

commentTextItems.html: back of a length, hooked through square leg

commentPreTextItems.html: Another change, with Lee back on. Still looking for that 381st ODI wicket, to draw level with Glen McGrath

commentTextItems.html: full and outside the line, driven through cover
quicker ball outside off, opens the face and runs this one down to third man - Australia just can't plug the leaks any more

dismissalText.commentary: Alastair Cook lbw b McKay 18 (18b 3x4 0x6 34m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: and there is a wicket with Cook caught on the crease and plumb lbw. Boy did Australia need that. Excellent delivery, good length around off stump, it shaped back to beat the forward push of Cook and caught him around the knee roll bang in front of middle

headshotImage.longCaption: Jonathan Trott player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Jonathan Trott player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Jonathan Trott player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: Trott advances on Watson, gets a faint inside edge, and the ball rattles the stumps! The ball was pretty similar to the one Bell hit out of the park but Trott played with an angled bat - where Bell's was straight - and Watson skidded it through the gap to disturb wicket. Trott's off and Aussies/aesthetes everywhere rejoice

and he does strike! Bell goes to cut a ball that slid onto him and loses his off stump. It was too full for the stroke and a poor stroke first ball to a new bowler anyway, and Bell missed it and it ran onto off stump

headshotImage.caption: Brett Lee player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Brett Lee player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: tossed up, tip and run to mid-off - and Brett Lee's direct hit sends Bopara back! That's a shame, he should have been there at the end, but a <del>matchwinning</del> [not yet, not yet] top knock from the Essex man
